    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-04T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-04T12:00:00-05:00" n="559"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d559">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 838.00/1040.</note>
                <head ana="#head_untitled-inferred-from-preceding-sibling-head">[Untitled]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-04T12:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 4, 1914, noon</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your December 1, 9 a.m. and December 2, 3 p.m. Department interprets last
                    paragraph of your December 2, 3 p.m., to indicate that you are in accord with
                    Department’s November 24, 5 p.m. You are therefore instructed to inform
                    Théodore: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>That the Department will extend provisional recognition upon the
                            appointment of a commission with full powers, satisfactory to you, in
                            accordance with Department’s telegraphic instructions dated November 12,
                            2 p.m., and November 16, 11 a.m. At the same time the Department is
                            ready to use its good offices with the Bank in accordance with the first
                            paragraph of its November 28, 8 p.m.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>Formal and complete recognition of Theodore as President will only be
                            extended after commission has signed satisfactory protocols at
                            Washington in accordance with Department’s November 24, 5 p.m.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Report whether you consider additional United States naval forces desirable in
                    Haitian waters at the present time. Department desires to be guided as far as
                    may be possible by your recommendations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
